latestPosts.caption:
Phad has always been more than just a painting. It's a storytelling tradition, where a narrator brings each scene to life through voice and song.

With Phad Samvad, we wanted to preserve that essence, but reimagine the experience for today's experience. And this was our way of making the tradition interactive, personal, and alive again.

Phad Artist: @vijaijosi

#arthshiladelhi #phadsamvad #pabujikiphad #dastangoi #rajasthan #traditionalstorytelling

Watching Phad Samvad come alive through people’s curiosity has been the most rewarding part of this journey.
From surprise to stillness, every reaction reminded us why storytelling matters.

#PhadSamvad #FlowingHeritage #InteractiveArt #PabujiKiPhad #TextileAsStoryteller #AnuvadInnovationStudio #ArthshilaDelhi #JSWFoundation #LivingTraditions

latestPosts.caption:
Something magical unfolded at the Flowing Heritage Exhibition, Arthshila Delhi. We brought the legendary Pabuji ki Phad to life—not just to be seen, but heard.

Through an interactive textile, we immortalised the Art of Phad Vanchan in our own way—letting people listen and experience the story like never before.

Grateful to @anjanasomany for the opportunity to be a part of this beautiful celebration of heritage. It allowed us to create something innovative that we've never done before. Huge thanks to @jsw.foundation and @arthshila_delhi for creating a space where tradition met innovation.

This beautiful Phad is painted by @vijaijosi

Closing Reception details: 
🗓 Sun, 27th Apr 2025
🕔 5 PM onwards
📍 Arthshila Delhi, Pocket B-19/1, Okhla Phase II, New Delhi

Join us this weekend for a special evening of performances 𝐉𝐮𝐠𝐚𝐥𝐛𝐚𝐧𝐝𝐢: 𝐑𝐞𝐭𝐞𝐥𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐚𝐝 featuring  Fouzia Dastango (@fouziadastango) and Ritesh Yadav (@rites._.ydv) and 𝐏𝐡𝐚𝐝 𝐁𝐚𝐚𝐧𝐜𝐡𝐧𝐚 𝐨𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐑𝐚𝐯𝐚𝐧𝐡𝐚𝐭𝐭𝐚 by Bhopa Sugnaram and Bhopi. 

This final celebration marks the close of our multidisciplinary craft and art exhibition exploring India’s deep and timeless connection with water—an elemental force that continues to inspire creativity, culture, and innovation. 

Exhibition on view till 27th April 2025.

Catch it before it leaves!

latestPosts.caption:
We’re wrapping up our exhibition series with a special lineup of events – and this weekend marks the final one!

Join us for the closing workshop 𝐖𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐫 𝐒𝐭𝐨𝐫𝐢𝐞𝐬 𝐢𝐧 𝐏𝐚𝐛𝐮𝐣𝐢 𝐤𝐢 𝐏𝐡𝐚𝐝 led by @vijaijosi
Step into the world of Phad Painting a traditional Rajasthani art form that tells stories through vibrant visuals and intricate details. 

𝐃𝐚𝐭𝐞: Sun, 27 Apr 2025 
𝐓𝐢𝐦𝐢𝐧𝐠𝐬: 2:30 PM - 4:30 PM
𝐋𝐨𝐜𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧: Arthshila Delhi, Pocket B-19/1, Okhla Phase II, New Delhi

🔗Registration link in bio (no fees required)

All materials will be provided – just bring your curiosity and creative spirit!

About the Artist:
Vijay Joshi is a renowned Phad artist from Shahpura, Rajasthan, celebrated for his dedication to preserving and innovating within this traditional art form. As the 13th-generation practitioner in his family, he learned the nuances of Phad painting under the guidance of his father, Shri Shantilal Joshi, a National Award winner in 1991.

🗓️ On view till 27th April 2025

Curated by @anjanasomany with scenography by @nambiar.aparna and @abhhay from @vertex_inc, the exhibition brings together a vibrant mix of voices: scholarship from @mulla_do_piaza, @footprints_earth, @judyfrater, and @ninasabnanis, contemporary works by @madeinearth.in, @bandeepsinghphotography, @anuvad_ by @chhail, @scenesbyrhea, @rutvajoshidesign, @ssahaworks and @harshverma.01 , alongside craft innovations by @shama_pawar, Dhanalakota Rakesh, and @vijaijosi .

Presented by Arthshila Delhi in partnership with @jsw.foundation, this exhibition invites you to explore the unseen and celebrate the fluid thread that connects India’s past, present, and future.

latestPosts.caption:
Anuvad Innovation Studio presents Phad Samvad, that reimagines the traditional Pabuji ki Phad, a centuries-old Rajasthani narrative scroll, using 21st-century technology. Displayed at Arthshila Delhi as part of the Flowing Heritage exhibition organized by JSW Foundation and curated by Anjana Somany, it offers a whole new way to experience folklore.

This gorgeous Phad is painted by @vijaijosi 

You know what's special about it? This Phad has 20 proximity sensors embedded into the fabric. We created something what we like to call a 'Magic Lantern' that enables the visitor to become an audience and a narrator at the same time, and listen to the Phad narration in Dastangoi style.
